s Marine Corps Reserve]]<br>[[Mississippi Army National Guard]]\n|serviceyears = Marine Corps Reserve: 1989\u20131996<br> Army National Guard: 1997\u2013present<ref name=\"AUSA2011\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ausa.org/legislation/congressionalinfo/Documents/OAS%20112th%20Congress.pdf |title=Once a Soldier... Always a Soldier |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2011 |work=Legislative Agenda |publisher=[[Association of the United States Army]] |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref>\n|rank         = [[File:Army-USA-OR-05.svg|20px]] [[Sergeant]]<ref name=\"AUSA2011\" />\n|unit         = \n|battles      = [[Gulf War]]<br>[[Iraq War]]<ref name=\"AUSA2011\"/>\n}}\n'''Steven McCarty Palazzo''' (born February 21, 1970) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|MS|4}} since 2011. The district takes in most of [[Mississippi]]'s share of the Gulf Coast and includes [[Biloxi]], [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]], [[Pascagoula]], [[Laurel, Mississippi|Laurel]] and [[Hattiesburg, Mississippi|Hattiesburg]]. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. Palazzo defeated 10-term [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic]] [[incumbent]] [[Gene Taylor (Mississippi)|Gene Taylor]] with 52% to 47% of the vote in the 2010 mid-term election. Previously, he served in the [[Mississippi House of Representatives]], having represented District 116 from 2006 to 2011. Palazzo again defeated Taylor in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Mississippi, 2014|June 2014 Republican primary election]]. Taylor switched parties in a bid to return to his former House seat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/senate-races/199634-ex-rep-gene-taylor-becomes-republican-to-run-again|title=Cameron Joseph, Ex-Rep. switches parties to run again|publisher=thehill.com|accessdate=March 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and military service==\nPalazzo was born February 21, 1970 in Gulfport.<ref>[http://billstatus.ls.state.ms.us/members/house/palazzo.xml  Steven Palazzo], Mississippi House of Representatives</ref> He enlisted in the [[Marine Corps Reserve]] in 1988, and served with the [[3rd Force Reconnaissance Company]] in the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]. He currently serves in the [[Mississippi Army National Guard]]. He received a [[Bachelor's]] and [[Master of Accountancy|MPA]] from the [[University of Southern Mississippi]], and is a member of the [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity. He is a [[Certified Public Accountant]].\n\n==Mississippi House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nIn April 2006, incumbent Republican State Representative Leonard Bentz of Mississippi's 116th House District resigned because he was appointed to the [[Mississippi Public Service Commission]]. Palazzo defeated Democratic candidate Maryann Graczyk, an education lobbyist, and Republican George Emile, a funeral home director, 51%-26%-24%.<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=396624]</ref> In 2007, running unopposed, he was elected to a full term.<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=396601]</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nPalazzo was awarded the 2009 Elected Official of the Year from the MS Wildlife Federation. The Mississippi Business Journal and the Sun Herald (2005) named Palazzo as a Top Business Leader under 40.<ref>[http://palazzoforcongress.com/about-steven-palazzo]</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nHe served on the Banking and Financial Services, Juvenile Justice, Labor, Select Committee on the Gulf Coast Disaster, and the Wildlife, Fisheries and Parks Committees.<ref>[http://billstatus.ls.state.ms.us/members/house/palazzo.xml Mississippi House of Representatives: Steven Palazzo] Accessed June 3, 2010</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Mississippi, 2010#District 4}}\nPalazzo entered the Republican primary for [[Mississippi's 4th congressional district]] and won the nomination with 57% of the vote. He faced 10-term Democratic incumbent [[Gene Taylor (Mississippi)|Gene Taylor]] in the general election. Although the 4th has turned almost solidly Republican at the federal level, Taylor had held the seat without serious difficulty. His voting record had been very conservative even by [[Mississippi Democratic Party|Mississippi Democratic]] standards, and he'd often broken with his party. Palazzo established himself as Taylor's strongest opponent since 1996. In particular, he attacked Taylor for supporting [[Nancy Pelosi]] for House Speaker in 2006 and 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1010/44119.html|title=Taylor: I voted for McCain - Jessica Taylor|publisher=Politico.Com|accessdate=2010-11-03}}</ref> He was endorsed by [[Sarah Palin]] and in the November 2010 general election, Palazzo defeated Taylor 52%-47%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=496790</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Mississippi, 2012#District 4}}\nIn the Republican primary, he defeated two challengers with 74% of the vote.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=751580</ref> In the November election, he defeated Democratic candidate Matthew Moore 64%-29%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=724373</ref>\n\n;2014\nIn the Republican primary, Palazzo defeated four challengers in the primary, including Gene Taylor, a Democrat-turned-Republican who served 22 year in Congress before Palazzo beat him in 2010. Palazzo won 50.5% of the vote while Taylor won 43% of the vote. Three minor candidates made up the reamianing percentage. Taylor actively campaigned and drew large numbers of Democrats into the Republican Primary.  <ref>http://msbusiness.com/blog/2014/06/05/palazzo-defeats-taylor-4th-congressional-district-primary/</ref>\n\nPalazzo will now face Democrat challenger Matthew Moore who he defeated 64%-29% in 2012.\n\n===Tenure===\nPalazzo voted with his Republican colleagues to pass a Balanced Budget Amendment, and force to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].\n\n===Legislation===\nPalazzo was one of the initial co-sponsors of the [[Social Media Working Group Act of 2014 (H.R. 4263; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security]] to establish within the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS) a [[social media]] working group (the Group) to provide guidance and best practices to the [[Emergency management|emergency preparedness and response]] community on the use of social media technologies before, during, and after a [[terrorist attack]].<ref name=4263sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4263 - Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4263|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> Palazzo stated that \"social media has played a crucial role in emergency preparedness and response in Mississippi, including during disasters like Hurricane Isaac and the tornadoes that hit the Hattiesburg area a little over a year ago.\"<ref name=WXXVreport>{{cite news|last1=Thomas|first1=Rachael|title=Palazzo Introduces Social Media Emergency Response Bill|url=http://www.wxxv25.com/news/local/story/Palazzo-Introduces-Social-Media-Emergency/oXdyZRilcE282zWtHC9_qg.cspx|accessdate=9 July 2014|publisher=Fox News 25 - WXXV|date=17 March 2014}}</ref> He said that their goal with the bill was to \"build upon existing public-private partnerships and use social media in a more strategic way in order to help save lives and property.\"<ref name=\"WXXVreport\"/>\n\nOn April 7, 2014, Palazzo introduced the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration Authorization Act of 2014 (H.R. 4412; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would [[authorization bill|authorize]] the [[appropriations bill (United States)|appropriation]] of $17.6 billion in fiscal year 2014 to the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] (NASA).<ref name=4412sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4412 - Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4412|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=cbo4412>{{cite web|title=CBO - H.R. 4412|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45376|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref> NASA would use the funding for human exploration of space, the [[Space Launch System]], the [[Orion (spacecraft)|Orion multipurpose crew vehicle]], the commercial crew program, the [[International Space Station]] (ISS), and various technological and educational projects.<ref name=\"4412sum\"/><ref name=HillNASAreauth>{{cite news|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|title=House passes NASA reauthorization|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/208739-house-passes-nasa-reauthorization|accessdate=10 June 2014|publisher=The Hill|date=9 June 2014}}</ref> Palazzo said that \"American leadership in space depends on our ability to put people and sound policy ahead of politics.\"<ref name=\"HillNASAreauth\"/>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Readiness|Subcommittee on Readiness]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space and Aeronautics|Subcommittee on Space and Aeronautics]] (Chairman)\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Research and Science Education|Subcommittee on Research and Science Education]]\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Investigations and Oversight|Subcommittee on Investigations and Oversight]]\n\n==Personal life==\nPalazzo is married to the former Lisa M. Belvin. He is a member of the Rotary, VFW,  NRA, MS Society of CPAs, USM Alumni Association; Boys & Girls Club Board Member; Marine Corps Association and AICPA.\n\n{{Portal|Biography|Mississippi|Politics|United States Marine Corps|United States Army}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://palazzo.house.gov Congressman Steven Palazzo] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.palazzoforcongress.com/ Steven Palazzo for Congress] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Mississippi/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Steven_Palazzo_%5BR-4%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = P000601 | ballot = Steven_Palazzo | nndb = 541/000257767 | votesmart = 69521 | govtrack = 412443 | opencong = 412443 | rollcall = 31432 | politifact = | fec = H0MS04120 | opensecrets = N00031958 | assets = steven-palazzo/ | legistorm = 2768/Rep_Steven_Palazzo_MS.html | followthemoney = 8965 | ontheissues = House/Steven_Palazzo.htm | congress = steven-palazzo/2035 | worldcat = | c-span = stevenpalazzo | imdb = 5149797 | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAlE0YMP }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gene Taylor (Mississippi politician)|Gene Taylor]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Mississippi's 4th congressional district]]|years=2011\u2013present}} \n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alan Nunnelee]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=322nd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mike Pompeo]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MS-FedRep}}\n\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\n| NAME              = Palazzo, Steven\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = American politician\n| DATE OF BIRTH     = June 6, 1906\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    = [[Gulfport, Mississippi]]\n| \n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palazzo, Steven}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Categor